{"id":"2304.14521","submitter":"Dmitry Fishman","authors":"Sergey S. Kharintsev, Aleksey I. Noskov, Elina I. Battalova, Liat\n  Katrivas, Alexander B. Kotlyar, Jovany Merham, Eric O. Potma, Vartkess A.\n  Apkarian, and Dmitry A. Fishman","title":"Enhanced light-matter interaction through photon-electron momentum\n  matching: converting silicon into a direct bandgap semiconductor","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics physics.app-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  Photons carry insufficient momentum on their own to induce indirect optical\ntransitions in semiconducting materials. Absorption of light in indirect\nsemiconductors such as silicon requires the assistance of lattice phonons to\nprovide the necessary momentum. Compared to direct bandgap systems, this\nrenders silicon less attractive material for a wide range of optoelectronic\napplications. In this work, we introduce an alternative mechanism to fulfill\nthe momentum-matching criterion for optical excitations in indirect\nsemiconductors. We experimentally demonstrate that, when confined to scales\njust below ~3 nm, photons acquire sufficient momentum to allow electronic\ntransitions without the assistance of a phonon. In such arrangement, both\nenergy and momentum can be conserved with two particles only, a photon and an\nelectron, converting previously indirect transitions into direct. This\npreviously overlooked aspect of light-matter interaction manifests itself in a\nmarked increase of optical transition probability. The new strategy presented\nhere provides opportunities for more efficient use of indirect semiconducting\nmaterials in the areas of photovoltaics, energy conversion, light detection and\nemission.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 27 Apr 2023 20:25:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-01"}
